    "body": [
        "I've recently started trying to get a hierarchical salt system set up with Syndic, and it all seems to work as expected, except for the mine. It seems that each syndic master has an isolated mine, which serves its minions independently. This is a problem for me for a couple of reasons:\n\nOn one hand, I have a central LDAP server that lots of services need to authenticate against. It puts its IP address in the mine, and other services get the IP out of the mine when configuring what LDAP server to talk to. With just one salt master this works very smoothly. Right now, I have the LDAP server configured by the master of masters, and its IP is in the mine for the master of masters. But when a service configured by a sub-master tries to get the LDAP server's IP address out of the mine, it gets nothing back. **The mine for the master of masters is not accessible to minions configured by sub-masters.**\n\nOn the other hand, I have the reverse problem. I have a DNS server, also configured by the master of masters, which takes IP addresses out of the mine, along with minion IDs, and sets up DNS so that services can be accessed over the nework using minion IDs as host names. In this case, the DNS service configured by the master of masters doesn't get mine entries for services configured by sub masters. **The mine for sub-masters is not accessible to minions configured by the master of masters.**\n\nUltimately, it looks like syndic isn't propagating the mine in either direction. My expectation would generally be for mine entries to propagate both up and down, essentially creating one large mine for the entire topology.\n"
    ],
