{
    "body": [
        "In many cases this likely half works in the interplay of ufuncs (which simply check for `PyErr_Occured()` and loops/cast methods, which also check and skip further evaluation if an error has already occured.\r\n\r\nA simple example for this is:\r\n```python\r\narr = np.array([1, 2, 3, None, 4], dtype=object)\r\ni = np.nditer(arr, flags=[\"refs_ok\", \"grow_inner\", \"buffered\", \"delay_bufalloc\"],\r\n                    op_dtypes=[\"int64\"], casting=\"unsafe\")\r\n# Does the actual casting/buffer filling\r\ni.reset()\r\n```\r\n(identical result without `\"delay_bufalloc\"` during nditer setup)\r\n\r\nRight now the transfer/cast functions are not capable of returning an error (same as ufunc loops). This is something that must be fixed, but even when it is fixed, `nditer` will need to be updated to stop looping when such an error occured. Additionally `nditer` users/cleanup would need to check for that.\r\n\r\nIn particular, `NpyIter_Dealloc` is already capable of returning an error value, but we do not actually check for it. Or alternatively, we may use a pattern of `do {...} while (err = iternext());` I suppose (although `NpyIter_Dealloc` is necessary in any case, the question is whether it will happen first thing after the loop always, at the end of the iteration a Python Error could be set, unless we store that error until `Dealloc` or some error probing function is called...)."
